        <p style="font-size:18px; line-height:1.2;">
          <strong>🇺🇦 Ukrainian parliament affirms Zelenskyy’s legitimacy</strong> 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> 
            Ukraine's parliament has reaffirmed Volodymyr Zelenskyy's presidency. 268 parliament members unanimously voted for a resolution asserting that <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-01-03-2025-r1-1-no-elections-can-be-held-until-martial-law-is-lifted?source=website" target="_blank">no elections can be held until martial law is lifted</a>. The vote rejects allegations made by Donald Trump and Vladimir Putin. Both presidents argue that Zelenskyy is illegitimate due to the lack of elections during the war. Zelenskyy’s mandate remains valid despite his term expiring last May. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> 
            The war has made elections impossible, with many Ukrainians abroad and many others fighting. Zelenskyy was willing to step down for peace or NATO membership, yet the parliament supported him. Article 108 of the Ukrainian constitution states that the incumbent head of state remains in power until the next elected president takes office. 
          </p>
          </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.2;">
          <strong>🇷🇸 The Serbian president made a mistake in the UN resolution</strong> 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          Serbian President Aleksandar Vučić apologized to citizens after Serbia voted in favor of a UN resolution. The resolution <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-01-03-2025-r2-2-called-for-a-just-and-lasting-peace?source=website" target="_blank">called for a just and lasting peace</a> in Ukraine. He admitted the vote was a mistake and took personal responsibility. He blamed it on fatigue influencing his decision. Serbia was among 93 countries supporting the resolution, which was backed by European nations but opposed by Russia and the US.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          Vučić later stated that Serbia should have abstained, as it did in the US-backed resolution. Russia accepted his apology, emphasizing that technical errors happen. Serbia, which has close ties to Russia, faces pressure to balance its relations with Moscow and the European Union. 
          </p>
          </mj-text>

          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:18px; line-height:1.2;">
          <strong>🇰🇷 Yoon's closing arguments in his impeachment trial</strong> 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> 
            South Korean President Yoon Suk Yeol <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-01-03-2025-r3-3-had-his-final-argument-in-court?source=website" target="_blank">had his final argument in court</a> this week. He is facing impeachment for declaring martial law in December 2024. Yoon argued it was necessary to address a national security crisis. He cited threats from North Korea and domestic anti-state elements and defended his actions by claiming they were within his constitutional powers.
          </p>
            <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> 
           The prosecution opposed this and argued that Yoon’s decision endangered the country and harmed national unity. Yoon’s defense also contended that no harm was done, as the military did not intervene in parliament. The Constitutional Court's verdict on his impeachment is expected by mid-March. South Korea will hold a presidential election within 60 days if he gets impeached.
          </p>
          </mj-text>
