          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:400; margin-top:2px;">Why is Ukraine not a part of NATO or the EU?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px; line-height:1.5;">While Ukraine wants to join the EU and NATO, it faces many obstacles. Although it has made strides against corruption, it remains a significant issue. The EU and NATO need democratic governance, the rule of law, and transparency, which Ukraine is still working to improve. NATO needs a modern military that meets its standards, which Ukraine has reformed since the conflict with Russia began in 2014.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px; line-height:1.5;">However, it still struggles with modernization and training. <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-01-03-2025-bq1-4-ukraine-cannot-join-until-the-conflict-ends?source=website" target="_blank">Ukraine cannot join until the conflict ends</a>. There is also no shortcut for EU membership. Each candidate is required to align its laws and standards with the EU across 35 policy areas, known as chapters. These cover many sectors, including trade, taxation, energy, the environment, and judicial rights.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px; line-height:1.5;">All 27 EU members must negotiate and approve each chapter, which is time-consuming and politically sensitive. The ongoing conflict with Russia has hurt Ukraine’s territorial integrity, especially in Crimea and the east. Both alliances are careful about admitting countries with unresolved territorial disputes since this complicates security and diplomacy.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px; line-height:1.5;">Russian resistance to Ukraine's Western integration adds to the challenges. Many in Ukraine support EU and NATO membership, but some regions are less enthusiastic, making the process harder. The EU is also cautious about newer members due to concerns over other countries' backsliding on key issues after joining, such as Hungary and Poland.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
